This is the crate root for `ctx-cage`, the sandbox that bounds an autonomous agent's blast radius during a run — filesystem, host namespaces, and network — but does not broker tools or mask source (that job moved to `ctx-context`; the agent uses native Read/Edit inside the cage). It re-exports the crate's submodules (`bwrap`, `cli`, `error`, `lifecycle`, `proxy`, `runtime`) and defines one constant.

The file itself has no logic beyond module wiring and one `include_str!`. The load-bearing fact: `CAGE_RULES_MD` embeds `../assets/cage-rules.md` at compile time, so the binary physically cannot ship without the agent doctrine text — editing the rules means editing that asset file, not this one, and a missing asset file is a build-time failure, not a runtime one. This constant is injected via `--append-system-prompt-file` on every real `claude` launch, per the module doc; any launcher code that constructs the `claude` invocation must keep using it or the safety doctrine silently stops being injected.

Key sandbox facts encoded only in the doc comment (not enforced here, but binding on `bwrap`/`runtime`): the workspace is mounted read-write at its real host path with no fixed alias (ADR-046); toolchain is read-only; `.env` and `.git/config` are masked even inside the workspace; nothing from `$HOME` is mounted; namespaces are fresh (user/pid/ipc/uts) with `--die-with-parent` and cleared env; `no_new_privs` is set unconditionally; a seccomp filter is called out as a known-missing residual. Networking is fully offline (`--unshare-net`) — the only egress is `proxy`, reached over a bind-mounted UNIX socket, which injects the real API key host-side so the raw key never enters the cage. Anyone modifying `bwrap.rs` or `runtime.rs` should keep these invariants consistent with this doc, since it's the canonical statement of what guarantees the cage makes.